2011 Winter Series (Blue Robin)

Well what an interesting series this has been the Blue Robin certainly lived up to its name. Despite the coldest winter on record and missing??? races due to a frozen lake 60 plus boats still managed to participate in the series and with a regular handicap fleet of 20 plus boats a big congratulations must go to the intrepid sailors at Tata.

The sailing was close and any one of 4 sailors could have won the series right up until the last day of sailing. However it was Keith Jones in his Streaker who held onto his lead, which he held for the last 4 weekends of the series. While Paul Govier in his Solo leading the series from the moment the qualification period was reached (race 8) came in a credible second. Gordon Evans and Bob Taylor, Fireball, finished third and were left licking their wounds hoping for more wind in next years Blue Robin.

Overall for the series the winds were on the light side and varied in direction, with running starts as the wind came from the unfavourable and very cold east on too many occasions. It was during one of these easterlies that the most damage was done to a certain Osprey of Andrew and Rebecca Jenkins, when a forestay problem lead to the mast deciding it did not like the conditions and broke in two.

It was very noticeable that in the Solos when part timers Cliff Crawshaw and Ian Fox decided to make an appearance they won, unfortunately for them but fortunately for the rest of us they did not attend sufficient races to qualify for the series.

So, yet another successful winter series completed and now all the hardcore sailors will wait to be joined by the warm weather (well warmer) sailors for the Spring 2011 series.

Series Appraisal given by Gordon Evans and Bob Taylor.
